# 1) Exact wording thresholds for humidity comfort

### Core principle

Humidity is **not about precision**, it’s about **comfort perception**.

Users do not think:

> “It’s 63% humidity”

They think:

> “This feels dry / fine / sticky”

So the card and overlay should *translate* humidity into comfort.

***

## Recommended humidity comfort bands

These thresholds are conservative, intuitive, and map well to real-world perception indoors and outdoors.

| Relative Humidity | Comfort Label      | Notes                               |
| ----------------- | ------------------ | ----------------------------------- |
| **0–20%**         | **Very dry**       | Dry skin, static, irritated airways |
| **20–30%**        | **Dry**            | Common in winter, still noticeable  |
| **30–50%**        | **Comfortable**    | Ideal range                         |
| **50–60%**        | **Slightly humid** | Some people notice                  |
| **60–70%**        | **Humid**          | Sticky, reduced comfort             |
| **70%+**          | **Very humid**     | Oppressive, sweat doesn’t evaporate |

✅ These labels are calm and descriptive  
✅ No alarmist wording  
✅ No medical claims

***

## How this appears in the UI

### Metric card (always show)

    Humidity
    58%
    Slightly humid
    [ sparkline ]

### Overlay (reinforce meaning)

Top block:

    58%
    Slightly humid

Supporting line (small):

> Comfort may decrease as humidity rises

***

## Optional nuance (only if you want it)

If you later incorporate temperature:

*   High temp + high humidity → “Muggy”
*   Low temp + high humidity → “Damp”

But **do not** add this now. What you have is already strong.

